  "why": "The paper provides partial diagnostic insight: it reports statistical failure patterns across environmental types (counts of detected errors under different error bounds) and explicitly uses neuron-level coverage metrics (KMNC and NBC) to characterise and compare the diversity of failure-inducing inputs. These measurements give useful, empirical information about where and when the models fail (e.g., which environmental types produce more errors and that styles causing higher coverage tend to reveal more diverse failures). However, the paper does not link these observed failures to underlying model vulnerabilities (such as reliance on spurious/non-robust features, dataset bias, or detailed neuron-activation analyses). The authors note that style vectors are hard to interpret and do not provide analyses that explain why the models fail under the discovered conditions, so the work stops at statistical and coverage-based diagnosis rather than root-cause attribution.",
  "evidence": "Page 4, Section 3.2: \"The key to the success of the search is a proper fitness function ... it is the combination of two effectiveness measures: (1) the ability to detect more diverse erroneous behaviours; and (2) the ability to detect more erroneous behaviours.\" (describes the coverage and steering-divergence measures used for diagnosis).\n\nPage 5, Section 3.2.1: \"...we carefully select two fine-grained coverage metrics on the sub-neuron level ... i.e., k-multisection Neuron Coverage (KMNC) and Neuron Boundary Coverage (NBC).\" (shows the use of neuron-level internal metrics to characterise failures).\n\nPage 7, Section 4.2 (Results): \"Compared with Rc, TACTIC achieves higher coverage in all environmental types, demonstrating that TACTIC can detect more diverse erroneous behaviours than Rc... In terms of the detected erroneous behaviours, compared with Rc and DeepRoad, TACTIC detects many more erroneous behaviours in all environmental types for both four error bounds.\" (reports statistical failure patterns by environmental type and error bound).\n\nPage 4, Section 3.2: \"the style space in MUNIT is a high-dimensional vector space, and hence, a style vector in the style space is difficult for interpretation.\" (acknowledges limited interpretability and absence of mapping from styles to specific visual features or vulnerabilities).\n\nNo section in the paper performs analyses that attribute failures to underlying vulnerabilities (e.g., spurious features, dataset bias, or per-neuron causal analyses); the paper focuses on coverage- and statistics-based identification of failure-inducing conditions (see overall Experimental Evaluation and Conclusion, e.g., Page 9: \"TACTIC can effectively identify critical environmental conditions and synthesise realistic testing driving scenes ... reveal more diverse and more erroneous behaviours\")."
